#Text=William Lucombe

#Text=William Lucombe ( before 1720 – after 1785 ) was a horticulturalist and nurseryman , who discovered and gave his name to the natural hybrid Lucombe Oak ( Quercus × hispanica ' Lucombeana ' ) , a semi-deciduous oak tree . [ 1 ] [ 2 ]
#Text=The Lucombe nursery
#Text=William Lucombe began his horticultural career as Head Gardener in the service of merchant Thomas Ball at Mamhead Park circa 1720 .

#Text=It was while working at Mamhead that he founded his nursery , the first commercial plant nursery in southwest England , [ 3 ] marketing many of the plants collected by Ball during the latter 's commercial travels abroad , most famously the Holm Oak . [ 4 ]
#Text=Lucombe bred his eponymous oak at his nursery in St Thomas , Exeter , which he founded in 1720 .
#Text=In 1794 , his son John Lucombe took possession of the nursery on Alphington Road , later known as the Exeter Nursery .
#Text=In 1801 , Benjamin Pince became a partner in the business , and by 1807 the nursery enterprise was trading as ' John Lucombe , Pince & Co ' .
#Text=At this time they bought the adjoining nursery of William Ford and Son on Alphington Street .
#Text=In 1824 , John Lucombe sold the business to Captain Robert Pince for £1500 .
#Text=The nursery flourished under his son Robert Taylor Pince , but began to decline in the late 19th century , and the site was sold to the city of Exeter in 1912 .
#Text=Part of the land became Pinces Gardens , a public park , part allotments and the remainder housing . [ 5 ]
#Text=Main trunk of the Lucombe Oak at Kew Gardens .
#Text=Lucombe Oaks
#Text=The natural hybrid Lucombe Oak was first spotted in 1762 when Lucombe noticed that one of the saplings produced from a Turkey Oak acorn he had planted kept its leaves in winter .
#Text=He later observed that these features occurred where both parent species grew , Quercus cerris ( Turkey Oak ) and Quercus suber ( Cork Oak ) .

#Text=True Lucombe Oaks are clones of the original tree , but the name ' Lucombe Oak ' is also often used to refer to any Spanish Oak , a frequently occurring hybrid between Turkey Oaks and Cork Oaks .
#Text=A large semi-evergreen tree developing a deeply furrowed bark when mature .
#Text=Leaves to about 12 x 5cm , glossy dark green above , grey beneath and edged with sharp teeth .
#Text=Raised at the Lucombe nursery , Exeter from seed of Q. cerris in about 1763 .
#Text=It produces viable seed and many seedlings of it have been distributed .
#Text=One of the early Lucombe Oaks went to Kew Gardens . [ 6 ]
#Text=Lucombe Oaks along with their descendants , which include back crosses with the naturalised Turkey Oak , are common in the landscape of East Devon , as well as in parks and gardens .
#Text=The Tree Register of the British Isles −TROBI Champion is at Phear Park in Exmouth , measuring 26 metres ( 85ft ) in height , with a trunk diameter of 261 centimetres ( 103in ) in 2008 . [ 7 ]
#Text=>
#Text=Lucombe felled the original hybrid in 1785 , keeping timber from it from which his coffin was to be made when he died .
#Text=He stored the boards under his bed .
#Text=However , he lived , for the age , an exceptionally long life , dying at the age of 102 years .
#Text=By that time the planks had decayed in the Devon dampness .
#Text=Instead , on his death , timber from one of his early graft propagations was used to make his coffin .
